s  with his neoexpressionist manner of painting and verbal m a nipulation charles constantly reinvents and reconfigures negative advertising stereotypes of african american characters and destroys their original debasement  his well painted scandalous broadsides are staged in a vibrant and sardonic visual language which challenges the viewer charless disturbing manipulations of racial images and stereotypes follows in t h e manner of s us representative to the venice biennale robert colescott for much of his career colescott has unstintingly appropriated icons of t h e western canon and turned them on their head and like colescottand kara walker charles revels in t h e explosive intercultural subtext of identity and negative stereotypes interracial sex and racebased icons i t is charless interrogation and subversion of sambos mammies and sportscelebrity icons which move these paintings thematic thrust onto theirtroubling turf the format charles employs is that of an enlarged advertising banner in which a retinue of little black sambos aunt j e m i m a s  pickaninnies negro court jesters celebrities sports icons and black face circus animals in harlequin pants make their stage appearances  thus charless antiquesurfaced advertising explosions and raggededge graphic takeoffs are elements of his fictitious and parodic product lines and merchandising campaigns forever slueperioc from t h e series  t h e liberty media o n paper courtesy of the artist free the liberty brothers permanent daily circus and the forever free post within these three artistic series charles e m ploys a brutal parody t o d e c o n struct negative y e t once popular malicious american concepts used to represent t h e many ideas once originally expounded in t h e nineteenth century doctrine of negrophobia however t h e c o m plexity of t h e subject charles e x plores leads one t o ask whether his idea of transgression is a t h o r oughly worked out critique of t h e stereotype or whether it is second generation appropriation whose use value is premised on its ordinary shock value and lack of critical dimension whatever one brothers permanently daily circus mixed makes of these works it is disturbing in a way that should lead to sober evaluation of its merits rather t h a n  as many who have chosen t o castigate t h e artist do simply dismiss i t  these alarming works go deep into neglected emotional sites where phobias reside michael ray charless works tour these obscure locations of personal and collective memory seeking t o unravel their incipient power and connection t o an ever present american neurosis i n t h e paintings we are confronted with images of such v i olence emblematic of t h e fear we all feel when recalling t h e damage inflicted by these appropriated signifiers in t h e former context we are confronted with this again and again in t h e multilayered visual and discursive assaults in works from t h e liberty brothers permanent daily circus series handi the smart asses s a circus ring takeoff of a tuxedoed ringleader commanding three dancing white horses the greatest blow on earth plays havoc with the popular promotional theme of the barnum and bailey circus with a large openmouthed negro gaping t o receive cunnilingus or perform felatio an army of clowns presents an army of exquisitely colored dancing negro clowns surging to t h e foreground white girl tv dinners if you would like to authenticate using a different subscribed institution that supports shibboleth authentication or have your own login and password to project muse click authenticate you are not currently authenticated view freely available titles book titles or journal titles purchaserental options available rent from deepdyve research areas art and architecture  african art recommend email a link to this page frequently downloaded view citation save citation related content disguise masks and global african art en mas carnival and perfomance art of the caribbean yoruba art and